Sep 4 2009 	They used window-type air-conditioners!	My travel agent asked me to go for this Triton Hotel because the neighbouring Marriott hotels were found full 2 days before the start of my business trip and I settled for it accordingly, as it was only for one night &quot;transit&quot; stay.The hotel location is convenient and the staff friendly, the common areas and the rooms are slightly worn out but acceptable.The main problem is that the rooms are equipped with &quot;window-type&quot; air-conditioning units which are noisy when operating, and gives no fresh air. [N.B.: Travellers who read this review may trust my judgement as I have been belonging to the property discipline for many years.]After switching on the units at night for 2 hours, the room becomes nothing but noisy and stuffy, lacking oxygen. To open the windows for fresh air means 2 other problems: firstly, my room (and may be half of the rooms in such hotel) faces the side lane where the refuse rooms of the hotel and other adjoining buildings are located and can catch such &quot;unforgettable&quot; smell; secondly, the service vehicles and refuse-collection vehicles in US operate at nights, with their dumping and travelling noises throughout the night-time.So, the result is: &quot;shallow-sleeping people&quot; like me cannot sleep.Fortunately, it was only for one night stay, and I presume I would not be returning again unless they install some centralized ventilation system with treated air.One point worth mentioning: the hotel's web-page didn't show any &quot;window-type&quot; air-conditioning units in any of their rooms' interior photos, and &quot;experienced people&quot; like me would return to the website and find from the exterior night-view photo some ideas of the &quot;window-type&quot; air-conditioning units along the dim facades. I wished I had noticed those &quot;window-type&quot; air-conditioning units before I agreed to my travel agent's former offer.	
